Project Summary

This project aims to understand PEV ownersâ preferences with respect to participating in the Smart Charging programs to improve grid resilience and enable greater integration of renewable energy onto the grid. The three-year project will be performed in two research thrusts:

  1. Thrust One: Measure and model PEV charging preferences using conjoint survey.
  2. Thrust Two: Simulate grid performance under different SMC and V2G scenarios.

The Smart Charging programs contain both SMC and V2G:

  1. SMC is short for âSupplier-Managed Chargingâ. It allows the charging stations to monitor, manage, and even restrict the charging process to optimize energy consumption.
  2. V2G is short for âVehicle-to-Gridâ. It allows bidirectional charging, so that the vehicle can discharge a certain amount of electricity back to the grid to further optimize energy consumption by balancing supply and demand.

The team is currently designing a pilot survey for the first thrust.

Access the pilot survey here: Pilot Survey

The second thrust is also in early stages, and we are coordinating with partners to begin modeling grid performance under different PEV loading scenarios.
